**INTERMEDIATE RISK**
 
Re-test in 3 - 6 hours to EXCLUDE myocardial infarction.
 
A rise and/or a later drop of hs-Troponin T by more than
30% is consistent with myocardial infarction. A change of
less than 30% is consistent with chronic causes of
myocardial damage such as myocarditis, severe hypertension,
acute or chronic heart failure, renal failure, etc.
All hs-Troponin T levels above 99th percentile (14 ng/L)
are predictive of future adverse cardiac events.
 
NB: Clinical findings such as symptoms of ischaemia, ECG
changes indicative of new ischaemia, pathological Q waves or
demonstration of a new area of infarction or disturbance of
a regional wall motility by imaging is essential for
interpretation of hs Troponin T.

The Vidas D-dimer is determined by an ELISA method, which is
currently considered the gold standard in D-dimer testing.

The test has an excellent negative predictive value, and a
negative result will rule out Venous Thromboembolic Disease
(VTE).  If there is a high clinical pre-test probability of
pulmonary embolism or DVT (Based on the Wells/Geneva score),
however, it is recommended that more definitive
investigations be done in addition to a D-dimer test.

A positive D-dimer result is not specific for VTE, but may
also be seen in consumptive coagulopathies, chronic illness,
prolonged bed-rest, pregnancy, renal insufficiency, post
trauma and surgery.
